name: Oxygen Delivery - West Zones/Shunts
question1: Define West Zones. What factors can cause shifts within the west zones? Discuss the effect of high and low V/Q on alveolar O2 and CO2 partial pressures
contents:
On the basis of these pressure relationships, three functional zones are described (West zones).

Zone 1 : PA > Pa > Pv (apex)

Zone 2 : Pa > PA > Pv. (middle)

Zone 3 : Pa > Pv > PA. (base)


  • What factors can cause shifts within the west zones:
  • in healthy subjects: Zone 1 = PA > Pa > Pv
  • Zone 1 does not exist. because arterial pressure is just sufficient to raise blood to the top of the lung and exceed alveolar pressure.
  • Zone 1 may be present in severe hypotension.
  • conversely during exercise pulmonary artery pressure is high eliminating existing zone 1 into zone II and moving the boundary between zone III and zone II upward.
  • Discuss the effect of high and low V/Q on alveolar O2 and CO2 partial pressures
  • The alveolar partial pressure of O2 and CO2 are determined by the ratio of ventilation to perfusion, which varies across the lung in the upright position,
  • At the apex of the lung V/Q ratio is highest about 3.0.
  • Here PaO2 is highest and PaCO2 is lowest (this explain why organisms that thrive in high o2 such as Tb flourish in the lung apex)
  • At the base of the lung V/Q ratio is lowest (about 0.6)
  • and now PaO2 is lowest and PaCO2 is highest.
question2: What do you understand by the term shunt? Categorise the types (2) What is the shunt equation?
contents2:
Shunt is an extreme form of V/Q mismatch whereby blood enters the arterial system without passing through ventilated areas of the lung.

It may be classified into intrapulmonary and extrapulmonary causes:


Intrapulmonary :

  • Physiological: bronchial arterial blood passing into the pulmonary veins. Coronary venous blood draining into the left ventricle
  • Pathological : lung collapse or consolidation with loss of ventilation

Extrapulmonary :

  • Cyanotic congenital heart disease: ie, right to left intracardiac shunting ie, tetralogy of fallot


limited increase in arterial P02 when FiO2 increased eg 1 lung vent.




Shunt fraction can be calculated with knowledge of:




  • CcO2 = oxygen content of blood at end of ventilated and perfused pulmonary capillaries
  • Assumed to be the same as alveolar O2; therefore estimated from alveolar gas equation
  • As a result require knowledge of PaCO2 and PiO2
  • CvO2 = oxygen content of mixed venous blood
  • CaO2 = oxygen content of arterial blood
  • No need for knowledge of flows or cardiac output
question4: Draw a curve to demonstrate how changes in minute ventilation affect the partial pressures of alveolar oxygen and alveolar carbon dioxide.
contents4:
The curve just shows what the Zones would dictate -

  • that is that PO2 would be highest at the apex's, with a correspondingly low pCO2.
  • that is that PO2 would be lowest at the base, with a correspondingly high pCO2. (because CO2 cannot be taken away because V/Q > 1) some element of shunt..
